### OKR Writing Guide
```yaml
# OKR Writing Guide

okr_fundamentals:
  objectives:
    definition: "Qualitative, inspirational statement of what you want to achieve"

    characteristics:
      - "Memorable and motivating"
      - "Directional, not specific"
      - "Time-bound (quarterly typical)"
      - "Ambitious but believable"
      - "Within team's influence"

    good_examples:
      - "Delight our customers with a world-class support experience"
      - "Become the market leader in enterprise security"
      - "Build a high-performing engineering culture"
      - "Transform our sales engine for sustainable growth"

    bad_examples:
      - "Increase revenue by 20%" # This is a KR, not an O
      - "Do more marketing" # Too vague
      - "Be the best" # Not actionable
      - "Launch product X" # This is a task/initiative

    writing_tips:
      - "Start with a verb (build, create, deliver, establish)"
      - "Make it inspirational - would you rally the team around it?"
      - "Avoid numbers - those belong in KRs"
      - "Ask: Does this matter? Will we remember it?"

  key_results:
    definition: "Quantitative, measurable outcomes that indicate achievement of the objective"

    characteristics:
      - "Specific and measurable"
      - "Outcomes, not outputs"
      - "Challenging but achievable (70% rule)"
      - "Clear success criteria"
      - "Time-bound (same period as objective)"

    good_examples:
      - "Increase NPS from 32 to 45"
      - "Reduce customer churn from 8% to 5%"
      - "Achieve $5M ARR from new enterprise accounts"
      - "Reduce mean time to resolution from 48h to 12h"
      - "Increase employee engagement score from 65 to 80"

    bad_examples:
      - "Improve customer satisfaction" # Not measurable
      - "Launch new website" # Output, not outcome
      - "Hire 5 engineers" # Activity, not result
      - "Be more efficient" # Not specific

    writing_formula:
      pattern: "Verb + specific metric + from X to Y"
      examples:
        - "Increase [metric] from [baseline] to [target]"
        - "Reduce [metric] from [current] to [goal]"
        - "Achieve [specific number] of [thing measured]"

    measurement_types:
      - type: "Baseline + target"
        example: "Increase retention from 85% to 92%"
        when: "You have historical data"

      - type: "Absolute target"
        example: "Achieve 100 enterprise customers"
        when: "Starting from zero or near-zero"

      - type: "Milestone"
        example: "Launch product to 100% of users"
        when: "Binary achievement needed"

      - type: "Percentage"
        example: "95% of support tickets resolved same-day"
        when: "Quality/consistency matters"

  alignment:
    vertical:
      description: "How OKRs cascade from company to team to individual"
      method:
        - "Company OKRs set by leadership"
        - "Teams set OKRs that support company OKRs"
        - "Individuals (optional) set OKRs that support team OKRs"
      alignment_strength:
        direct: "Team KR directly matches Company KR"
        supporting: "Team KR contributes to Company KR"
        adjacent: "Team KR enables Company KR indirectly"

    horizontal:
      description: "How teams coordinate across boundaries"
      method:
        - "Shared OKRs for cross-functional initiatives"
        - "Dependencies explicitly identified"
        - "Regular cross-team check-ins"

  scoring:
    google_method:
      scale: "0.0 to 1.0"
      interpretation:
        "0.0-0.3": "Failed to make real progress"
        "0.4-0.6": "Made progress but fell short"
        "0.7": "Target - stretched and achieved most of goal"
        "0.8-1.0": "Exceptional, possibly set too easy"

    simple_method:
      scale: "Percentage complete"
      status:
        green: "70-100% - On track"
        yellow: "40-69% - At risk"
        red: "0-39% - Off track"

    binary_method:
      options: "Yes/No - Did we achieve it?"
      when: "For milestone-based KRs"

  common_mistakes:
    - mistake: "Too many OKRs"
      fix: "Limit to 3-5 objectives, 3-5 KRs each"

    - mistake: "Sandbagging (easy goals)"
      fix: "Set ambitious targets, celebrate 70%"

    - mistake: "Measuring activities, not outcomes"
      fix: "Ask 'So what?' - what does this achieve?"

    - mistake: "Forgetting about OKRs until quarter end"
      fix: "Weekly check-ins, visible tracking"

    - mistake: "Linking OKRs to compensation"
      fix: "Keep separate, focus on learning"

    - mistake: "No baseline data"
      fix: "Measure current state before setting target"

    - mistake: "100% top-down"
      fix: "60% top-down, 40% bottom-up"
```

### OKR Implementation Playbook
```markdown
# OKR Implementation Playbook

## Phase 1: Preparation (Week 1-2)

### Executive Alignment
| Activity | Participants | Duration | Output |
|----------|--------------|----------|--------|
| OKR education | Leadership team | 2 hours | Shared understanding |
| Why OKRs discussion | Leadership team | 1 hour | Clear purpose |
| Implementation scope | Leadership team | 1 hour | Rollout plan |
| Success criteria | Leadership team | 1 hour | How we'll measure success |

### Design Decisions
| Decision | Options | Recommendation |
|----------|---------|----------------|
| Cadence | Annual / Quarterly / Monthly | Quarterly for most |
| Levels | Company only / Company + Team / All levels | Start Company + Team |
| Tool | Spreadsheet / Dedicated tool | Start simple |
| Transparency | Limited / Partial / Full | Full transparency |
| Scoring | Google (0-1) / Percentage / Binary | Percentage |

### Communication Plan
| Audience | Message | Channel | Timing |
|----------|---------|---------|--------|
| Leadership | Why OKRs, expectations | Meeting | Week 1 |
| All managers | OKR overview, training | Workshop | Week 2 |
| All employees | What's changing, why | All-hands | Week 3 |

---

## Phase 2: First OKR Cycle (Quarter 1)

### Week 1-2: Company OKRs
| Day | Activity | Participants | Output |
|-----|----------|--------------|--------|
| Day 1 | Strategic context review | Leadership | Shared context |
| Day 2-3 | Objective brainstorming | Leadership | 8-10 objective candidates |
| Day 4 | Objective prioritization | Leadership | 3-5 objectives selected |
| Day 5-7 | KR definition | Leadership | Draft KRs for each objective |
| Day 8-10 | Refinement & finalization | Leadership | Final Company OKRs |

### Week 3-4: Team OKRs
| Step | Activity | Owner | Notes |
|------|----------|-------|-------|
| 1 | Share Company OKRs | CEO | All-hands or document |
| 2 | Team alignment discussions | Team leads | Which company OKRs to support |
| 3 | Team OKR drafting | Teams | 2-3 objectives per team |
| 4 | Cross-team alignment | OKR Facilitator | Check dependencies |
| 5 | Team OKR finalization | Team leads | Final team OKRs |

### Week 5+: Execution
| Cadence | Activity | Participants | Purpose |
|---------|----------|--------------|---------|
| Weekly | Team check-in | Team | Update progress, surface blockers |
| Weekly | Company status update | All | Transparency, momentum |
| Bi-weekly | Cross-team sync | Team leads | Coordination |
| Mid-quarter | Company review | Leadership | Course correction |
| End quarter | Scoring & retrospective | All | Learning, celebration |

---

